The '''Association of Independent Maryland and DC Schools''' is an American nonprofit education organization representing 120 [[independent school]]s in the US state of [[Maryland]] and the [[District of Columbia]]. Based in [[Glen Burnie, Maryland]], it was founded in 1967 as the '''Association of Independent Maryland Schools''' (AIMS) and is a member of the [[National Association of Independent Schools]] (NAIS) and the NAIS Commission on Accreditation.
The Association provides [[Educational accreditation|accreditation]] services for its member schools as well as support for professional and institutional development. It also organizes regional Admissions Fairs,<ref>Colbert, Judy (2010). [https://books.google.com/books?id=OIzDCZDSNXgC&pg=PA159&dq=%22Association+of+Independent+Maryland+Schools%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=y6pYT_TmM6Wm0QXT57XwDQ&ved=0CEoQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Association%20of%20Independent%20Maryland%20Schools%22&f=false ''Insiders' Guide to Baltimore''], 6th ed., p. 159. Globe Pequot. {{ISBN|0762756705}}</ref><ref>''[[Baltimore Afro-American]]'' (5 October 1982). [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=2dAmAAAAIBAJ&sjid=xAIGAAAAIBAJ&pg=4652,1795667&dq=association-of-independent-maryland+schools&hl=en "Project for Black Students Begins"]</ref> and it acts as a public advocate for the independence of its members from government regulation. ==Member schools== The 120 schools accredited by the Association of Independent Maryland and DC Schools include: *[[Bullis School]] *[[Calverton School]] *[[Garrison Forest School]] *[[Gilman School]] *[[Glenelg Country School]] *[[The Gunston School]] *[[The John Carroll School]] *[[Lowell School (Washington, DC)]] *[[Mercy High School (Baltimore, Maryland)]] *[[Pride School of RZ arts]] *[[Seneca Academy and Circle School]] *[[Sidwell Friends School]] *[[St. Anne's School of Annapolis]] *[[St. James School, Maryland]] *[[Thornton Friends School]] *[[Waldorf School of Baltimore]]
